==Honours==
The rivalry reflected in El Clásico matches comes about as Real Madrid and Barcelona are the most successful football clubs in Spain. As seen below, [[Football records in Spain#Most successful clubs overall (official titles, 1903–present)|Barcelona leads Real Madrid 93–89]] in terms of official overall trophies.<ref>Copa Eva Duarte (Defunct) is not listed as an official title by the UEFA, but it is [http://www.rfef.es/noticias/supercopa/conoce-antecedentes-supercopa considered as such by the RFEF], as it is the direct predecessor of the Supercopa de España</ref> While the Inter-Cities Fairs Cup is recognised as the predecessor to the UEFA Cup, it was not organised by [[UEFA]]. Consequently, UEFA does not consider clubs' records in the Fairs Cup to be part of their [[UEFA#Competitions|European record]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/history/index.html |title=UEFA Europa League: History: New format provides fresh impetus |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref> However, [[FIFA]] does view the competition as a major honour.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/club=1903416/index.html |title=Classic Football: Clubs: FC Barcelona |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=14 August 2014}}<br>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/club=31083/index.html |title=Classic Football: Clubs: AS Roma |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref>

