"'''Enough Is Enough'''" is a 29-page resignation letter written by Davison L. Budhoo, an economist from [[Grenada]]. Budhoo served as a senior economist at the [[International Monetary Fund|International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) for 12 years until May 1988.<ref name="Danaher1994">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XK6Egbw4-PcC&pg=PA20|title=50 Years is Enough: The Case Against the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund|author=Kevin Danaher|publisher=South End Press|year=1994|isbn=978-0-89608-495-7|pages=20–}}</ref> His public resignation letter was sent to [[Michel Camdessus]], the then managing directory of the IMF.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.larouchepub.com/eiw/public/1990/eirv17n17-19900420/eirv17n17-19900420_013-budhoo_to_organize_to_halt_imf_c.pdf|format=PDF|title=Budhoo to organize to halt IMF crimes|author=Ronald Kokinda|work=EIR (Executive Intelligence Review)|volume= 17 |number= 17 |date= 20 April 1990|website=|accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref> The letter accused the IMF of extensive and systematic statistical fraud, which was then used to impose policies on developing countries.<ref name="countercurrents">{{cite web|url=https://countercurrents.org/2016/07/31/enough-is-not-enough-is-kerala-poised-for-social-darwinism/|title=Enough Is ‘Not’ Enough: Is Kerala Poised For Social Darwinism? |author= K. M. Seethi|work= Countercurrents|date=31 July 2016|website=|accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref> Budhoo claimed that the consequences of these policies led to massive poverty and starvation.<ref name="countercurrents" /> The Canadian author [[Naomi Klein]] reported on the letter in her 2007 book, ''[[The Shock Doctrine]]''.<ref name="skwakbox">{{cite web|url=https://skwawkbox.org/2012/08/27/proven-imf-brings-down-economies-intentionally/|title=Proven: IMF brings down economies intentionally|date=27 August 2012|website=Skwawkbox.org|accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref>
