A '''retirement savings account''' is a type of [[retirement plan]] account that is envisioned to replace all three different types of [[individual retirement account]]s that are currently used in the United States: [[traditional IRA]], [[Roth IRA]] and [[SIMPLE IRA|Simple IRA]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.investopedia.com/articles/personal-finance/111314/5-essential-retirement-savings-accounts.asp|title=Savings Account|last=Staff|first=Investopedia|date=2003-11-25|work=Investopedia|access-date=2018-05-19|language=en-US}}</ref> Contributions would be made on an after-tax basis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://roth-ira.net/faqs/how-will-i-calculate-my-ira-deduction/|title=How Will I calculate my IRA deduction|website=roth-ira.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> This is a major part of what the [[George W. Bush]] Administration's called the [[ownership society]].
