'''Vivelin of Strasbourg'''<ref group=note>He was also known as “{{lang|la|Vivelin Rufus}}” (Latin), “{{lang|fr|Vivian le Rous}}” (French), or “{{lang|de|Vivelin der Rote}}” (German), which all means “Vivelin the Red”.</ref> (d. after 1347) was an [[Ashkenazi Jews|Alsatian Jewish]] financier in the 14th century, presumably one of the richest persons within the [[Holy Roman Empire]] in that time.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mentgen |first=Gerd |chapter=Die Strassburger Juden Vivelin der Rote und Simon von Deneuvre: Bankiers europäischer Fürsten im 14. Jahrhundert |title=Porträt einer europäischen Kernregion: Der Rhein-Mass-Raum in historischen Lebensbildern |editor1-first=Franz |editor1-last=Irsigler |editor2-first=Gisela |editor2-last=Minn |year=2005 |location=Trier |publisher=Kliomedia |pages=131–137 |isbn=3-89890-087-8 |language=de}}</ref> He lived in [[Strasbourg]] and primarily dealt with the [[Electorate of Trier|Archbishop of Trier]], [[Baldwin of Luxembourg]], but also with the [[Kingdom of England|King of England]], [[Edward III of England|Edward III]], as he led a consortium that lent 140,000 [[florin]]s to Edward III on the eve of the [[Hundred Years' War]], in 1339.<ref>London, The National Archives, Public Record Office, C 67/17, m 3.</ref>

He is not found in documents after 1347, and might have died during the [[Strasbourg massacre|Strasbourg pogrom of 1349]], which saw almost 2,000 people being [[Death by burning|burned alive at the stake]].<ref>{{Google books |plainurl= |id=6uK5pa3R4d8C |page=203 |title=Codex Judaica: Chronological Index of Jewish History, Covering 5,764 Years of Biblical, Talmudic & Post-Talmudic History }}</ref>

